Welcome to §b§cA§bD§eG §e§0§rGregic Dimensions! This modpack is centered around §3GregTech CE: Unofficial§r, however several §5Magic§5§r mods are also featured, including Nature's Aura, Bewitchment, Roots, Astral Sorcery, Botania, and Blood Magic! In addition to these magic mods being required for progression, each one is associated with and gated behin§c§d§rd a §c§r§cdimension§r. For example, Astral Sorcery temples and ores can only be found in the Aether, and Botania requires the Twilight Forest. Tech is also gated behind the various dimensions, as most ore veins cannot be found in the overworld.

This chapter delves into the §7§7stone ag§8§8§r§r§7e §rof the pack, which is focused around PyroTech, Nature's Aura, Roots, and Tinkers' Construct. Good Luck!

Exploring the world, you may notice some things. Most significantly, you cannot punch trees to collect wood! This is caused by the mod PyroTech, which significantly overhauls Stone Age progression. To proceed, you will need to collect a few things.

§7Rocks§r: Can be found on the ground in most areas and collected by breaking.

§2§2§a§2Sticks§r: Can be obtained by breaking leaves on trees.

§aPlant Fibers§r: Can be obtained by breaking grass.

Now that you have collected the three basic things needed to get started in PyroTech, you can craft Crude Tools! These are PyroTech's equivalent of wooden tools, and only have 32 durability.

Let's make a deal: Craft a §7Crude Pickaxe§r, and I'll give you the rest of the tools.

Now that you can use your crude axe to chop wood, one other thing you may notice is that you cannot turn said wood into planks in a crafting grid. For that, you will need to craft a §aChopping Block §rby putting a wooden log in the crafting grid with your crude axe. However, be warned! The chopping block has a limited lifespan, and it will eventually break after several uses. It may be best to craft several.

Using your chopping block, you can now craft §aplanks§r. You can also craft wooden §2slabs§r§r, and you can use one slab and one log to craft a §4Worktable§r, your first form of 3x3 crafting. To use the worktable, right-click the items for the recipe into their designated slots. Then, right-click the table a few times with a §7Hammer§r.

The §7Mortar and Pestle§r from §aRoots§r allows you to grind certain items down early on. In this pack, its primary purpose is to allow you to obtain §7Silk Thread§r, an early form of String. To use the Mortar and Pestle, simply place the mortar on the ground, right click to place the ingredient(s) in, then right click with the pestle.

You may notice that you occasionally get §eSilkworm Eggs§r when breaking leaves. If these eggs are right-clicked on the ground, there is a chance to spawn a §eSilkworm§r. These creatures will occasionally drop §7silk cocoons§r, which can be ground into §7Silk Thread§r.

Using your newly crafted §8Mortar and Pestle§r, go ahead and make some §7Silk Thread§r.

Not only can §7Silk Thread §rbe crafted into String, it will also be used for Drying Racks in the next quest.
With a Crude Axe, you can now obtain wood! Go ahead and collect some.
With the §6Drying Rack§r, you are able to dry your regular §2Plant Fibers§r, as well as create §6Straw§r from wheat.
Now that you have access to tools, particularly the §7Crude Hoe§r, now might be a good time to set up a simple §eWheat Farm§r. Go collect some §aseeds§r by breaking grass!
After waiting for some time, you should be able to harvest the §6Wheat§r from your farm. Come back to this quest when you have collected eight §6Wheat§r for an easy §cA§bD§eG§r coin.

With access to planks and slabs comes the ability to store items! The vanilla chest, however, is further gated. Yet, PyroTech offers two alternatives, the Crate and the Shelf! Like crafting in the worktable, items can be stored in these by right-clicking them into the storage slots.

Now that you have obtained 3x3 crafting, You can obtain better tools in the form of §3GregTech §rtools, made from flint. The flint axe is particularly helpful, as it can chop down an entire tree by only breaking the bottom log.
§3GregTech's §rFlint Weapons are also useful early game, as any mob attacked with them will be lit on fire, as they are automatically enchanted with §cFire Aspect II§r.
Now that you have some basic weapons, go kill some animals and collect some meat! Any type of raw meat is accepted for this quest.

Crop growth acceleration this early on? Un-bee-lievable!!

Yes, that's right, §6Bees§r from Rustic can be placed in an Apiary to accelerate crop growth.

The §6Apiary§r from Rustic can house up to 64 §6Bees§r, which can accelerate crop growth while simultaneously producing §6Honeycombs§r. I personally recommend placing an apiary above the water source block of a 9x9 farm plot for optimal efficiency.

The Book of Shadows is your best friend.

betterquesting:10.desc:8:
Welcome to the Low Voltage (LV) Age! LV is the first of many tiers in GregTech, and like all of the other tiers, it has a corresponding metal to that tier (Steel), and an end goal in mind (Aluminium).

Your first task will be to generate GT power, which can be done using the Steam you should already be passively producing. See the quest to the left for a more detailed explanation of GT power.

GregTech power is its own beast. Unlike most mods that only care about the current of electricity, GT cares about two other factors from the real world: Amperage & Voltage.

Voltage in GT is determined by tiers (LV, MV, HV, etc.). Paying attention to those tiers are super important, as you cannot connect mis-matching tiers. If you try to push MV power through an LV cable, it will burn. The same is true if you connect a machine to cables of a higher voltage, as the machine will blow up.

Amperage is also just as important. Rather than many mods that supply as much power as the cables can transfer, the Amperage (or Amps) of GT wires determine how many Amps of the certain Voltage Tier it can supply. For example, if you are using 4-Amp LV wires, you can only supply UP TO 4 amps of 32 EU/t (given that you are generating that much power) to the machines connected. If you try to run more machines than your cables can handle, they will power off.

The final thing to note is EU-Loss. Most GT cables have a component called EU-Loss per block, which is how much EU will be lost for every block it travels. However, lossless cables exist that don't lose EU, and you will be able to craft them soon.

GT uses unique machine components for crafting every machine. Beyond the Machine Hull you have already crafted, there are also individual parts: Motors, Pumps, Robot Arms, Conveyor Belts, and Pistons. Each Voltage Tier has their own version of these parts, and they are used heavily throughout the tiers, so it is recommended you batch craft a whole bunch at a time. Also, crafting them kind of sucks.

Beyond being used to craft machines, Pumps, Conveyors, and Robot Arms also have other uses. When right clicked on the side of a machine, they can be used to import/export items or fluids. You can configure them by using a screwdriver on that face of the machine, but they have limits based on the voltage tier they are.

There are also the rarely used Emitters and Sensors. You will very rarely use them in recipes, so you don't need to craft that many.
The LV Centrifuge & Distillery have been blocked behind MV. The necessary recipes are now done in the Bewitchment Distillery and other relevant machines.
Automate Ore Mining / Processing ASAP! You are going to need a lot of materials moving forward, so it is highly recommended you start now!
Make your first Electric Blast Furnace!!!

betterquesting:10.desc:8:
Al-u-min-i-um. Not A-lum-i-num. 

Aluminium is the next main metal, and one of your two gateways into MV. To make it, you'll need to process your newfound Aether Gems (§bAquamarine§r, §dGravitite§r,§5 Zanite§r) in your Electric Blast Furnace.


There are three ways you can process them into Aluminium:

1.) You can put the gems §ldirectly§r in the EBF. This is the 'fastest' way you can do it.

2.) You can §l§r§lpulverize§r the gems, and put that dust in the EBF. This way is 'slower' than the first, and only really useful if you want to avoid getting the Dark Ashes by-product.

3.) You can §lpulverize§r the gem and §lelectrolyze§r the dust, which will get you Aluminium dust that you can smelt directly into ingots. This way is the 'slowest' but lets you directly get the ingots. (As a side note, you will need to start electrolyzing these gems to get access to §9Primal Mana§r for your magic progression, so maybe investing in this early could be worth it)


Either way you chose to produce it, you will need §la lot§r of Aluminium, so it is recommended you batch craft as much of this as you can. This quest only asks for 1 ingot, but you will need around a stack or two to really get started with MV.

You may notice that most quests provide different types of §6coins§6§r as rewards, depending on the current tier of tech you are in. These coins, known as §b§cA§bD§eG §6coins§r§r, exist for every tier of GregTech voltage, and can be used to buy basic materials and items. For the stone age, you can buy items using a 3x3 crafting grid. However, for steam age and onward, a single-block GregTech machine known as the §3Vending Machine§r§r exists for you to spend your coins.

Make sure to be checking out and following the respective Magic Lines throughout LV. In this chapter, you'll open up two new pathways for magic: Astral Sorcery via the Aether and Botania via the Twilight Forest, which will both be required to advance.
Sticks and Stones may break my bones, but Bronze will never hurt me.
